TI  - STRATEGIES OF SURVIVAL FOR WOOD SPECIES IN DEFICIENT ENVIRONMENTS FOR PHOSPHORUS IN THE AMAZON
T2  - HOLOS
AB  - The secondary forests (capoeiras) situated in the Northeast of Para generally used for shift agriculture, where phases of regeneration are intercalated with agricultural culture, are characterized currently for low soil fertility among others reflected factors for the reduced concentrations of available phosphorus (P). However, some common species in these forests as Neea macrophylla and Cecropia palmata develop strategies in the partition of P that allow the accumulation in potential of the nutrient in its leaves tissues, suggesting a rich mulch in P, which can become an alternative of P organic increment in local Agroforests Systems. Although the stock of P, can arrive up to 2 and 3 kg of P in leaves and primary stems for tree of Neea macrophylla, the P Use Efficiency for the potentially accumulative species were very low, demonstrating to be a mechanism of tolerance to environments with P deficit.
